.TH "TILDR\-CONFIG" "1" "2026" "Tildr" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
tildr\-config \[em] configuration reference for Tildr
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[CR]\[ti]/.config/tildr/config.toml\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Tildr stores its user configuration in TOML format at
\f[CR]\[ti]/.config/tildr/config.toml\f[R].
.PP
If the XDG config directory is unavailable, Tildr falls back to
\f[CR]$HOME/.config/tildr/config.toml\f[R].
.PP
The config file is created by \f[B]tildr init\f[R].
It can also be updated by \f[B]tildr import\f[R] and when Tildr saves a
selected GPG key.
If the file does not exist at startup, all default values are applied
silently.
.SH CONFIGURATION SECTIONS
.SS [core]
The \f[CR][core]\f[R] section controls general Tildr behavior.
.TP
\f[B]core.repo\f[R]
Repository path used by the CLI.
Accepts \f[CR]\[ti]/...\f[R], \f[CR]$HOME/...\f[R], or an absolute path
inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R].
The repository must be inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R] and cannot be
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R] itself.
Default: \f[CR]\[ti]/.dotfiles\f[R]
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][core]\f[R]
repo = \[dq]\[ti]/.dotfiles\[dq]
.EE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]core.search_threshold\f[R]
Number of managed files above which interactive pickers show a
search/filter step before the selection list.
Type a fragment to filter by fuzzy match, or press enter to skip.
Default: \f[CR]15\f[R]
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][core]\f[R]
search_threshold = 20
.EE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]core.color\f[R]
When \f[CR]false\f[R], disables all colored output by setting
\f[CR]NO_COLOR=1\f[R] before dispatch.
The \f[CR]NO_COLOR\f[R] environment variable is also respected
regardless of this setting.
Default: \f[CR]true\f[R]
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][core]\f[R]
color = false
.EE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]core.file_manager\f[R]
Optional file manager executable used when Tildr opens a directory.
When empty or unset, Tildr uses the system default file manager.
On Linux, that usually means the XDG \f[CR]inode/directory\f[R]
association.
Default: empty
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][core]\f[R]
file_manager = \[dq]nautilus\[dq]
.EE
.PP
This setting is used by \f[B]tildr open\f[R].
Interactive file pickers, such as \f[B]tildr add\f[R] with no path, are
handled by the platform file picker backend and do not use this setting.
.RE
.SS [git]
The \f[CR][git]\f[R] section controls Git integration.
.TP
\f[B]git.available\f[R]
Whether Git was detected by \f[B]tildr init\f[R].
Written automatically by Tildr and used by Git\-aware commands such as
\f[B]sync\f[R], \f[B]git status\f[R], and auto\-commit flows.
Default when no config exists: \f[CR]true\f[R]
.RS
.PP
This value is updated automatically when you run \f[CR]tildr init\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]git.enable\f[R]
Optional manual override.
When explicitly set to \f[CR]false\f[R], Tildr skips Git operations even
if Git is installed and \f[CR]git.available = true\f[R].
Default: unset
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][git]\f[R]
enable = false
.EE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]git.auto_commit\f[R]
When \f[CR]true\f[R], Tildr automatically runs \f[CR]git add \-A\f[R]
and \f[CR]git commit\f[R] after \f[B]add\f[R], \f[B]restore\f[R],
\f[B]del\f[R], \f[B]mv\f[R], \f[B]secret\f[R], \f[B]exclude\f[R],
\f[B]group\f[R], and \f[B]profile\f[R].
It also commits pending repository changes before \f[B]sync\f[R]
fetches, pulls, merges, or pushes.
Does not affect \f[B]apply\f[R], \f[B]unlink\f[R], \f[B]git\f[R], or
read\-only commands.
Default: \f[CR]true\f[R]
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][git]\f[R]
auto_commit = true
.EE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]git.sync_remote\f[R]
Remote used by \f[B]tildr sync\f[R] when the current branch has no Git
upstream configured.
Default: unset
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][git]\f[R]
sync_remote = \[dq]origin\[dq]
.EE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]git.sync_branch\f[R]
Remote branch used with \f[CR]git.sync_remote\f[R].
When unset, \f[B]tildr sync\f[R] uses the current local branch name.
Default: unset
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][git]\f[R]
sync_remote = \[dq]origin\[dq]
sync_branch = \[dq]main\[dq]
.EE
.RE
.SS [crypto]
The \f[CR][crypto]\f[R] section controls GPG encryption for sensitive
files.
.TP
\f[B]crypto.mode\f[R]
Encryption mode used by \f[B]tildr secret\f[R].
Accepted values:
.RS
.PP
\f[CR]symmetric\f[R] \[em] passphrase\-only encryption using GPG
symmetric AES\-256.
No key pair required.
The same passphrase must be used to decrypt on any machine.
.PP
\f[CR]asymmetric\f[R] \[em] encryption using an existing GPG key pair.
The recipient is set via \f[CR]crypto.gpg_key\f[R].
Decryption uses the private key and requires no additional passphrase
(subject to GPG Agent caching).
.PP
Default: \f[CR]symmetric\f[R]
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][crypto]\f[R]
mode = \[dq]symmetric\[dq]
.EE
.RE
.TP
\f[B]crypto.gpg_key\f[R]
GPG key ID or email address used when
\f[CR]crypto.mode = \[dq]asymmetric\[dq]\f[R].
When empty, Tildr prompts interactively on first use and saves the
chosen key to this field automatically.
Ignored when \f[CR]crypto.mode = \[dq]symmetric\[dq]\f[R].
Default: empty
.RS
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][crypto]\f[R]
mode = \[dq]asymmetric\[dq]
gpg_key = \[dq]william\[at]email.com\[dq]
.EE
.RE
.SH FULL EXAMPLE
.IP
.EX
\f[B][core]\f[R]
repo = \[dq]\[ti]/.dotfiles\[dq]
search_threshold = 15
color = true
\f[I]# file_manager = \[dq]nautilus\[dq]\f[R]

\f[B][git]\f[R]
available = true
auto_commit = true
sync_remote = \[dq]origin\[dq]
sync_branch = \[dq]main\[dq]

\f[B][crypto]\f[R]
mode = \[dq]symmetric\[dq]
\f[I]# gpg_key = \[dq]william\[at]email.com\[dq]   # only used when mode = \[dq]asymmetric\[dq]\f[R]
.EE
.SH PATH RESOLUTION RULES
Most path arguments to Tildr commands are interpreted relative to
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R].
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]tildr add .config/nvim/init.lua\f[R] resolves to
\f[CR]$HOME/.config/nvim/init.lua\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]tildr add \[ti]/notes/todo.md\f[R] resolves via the home shorthand
.IP \[bu] 2
Absolute paths are accepted only if they still point inside
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.PP
For \f[CR]tildr init \-\-repo\f[R], the path may be provided as:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]\[ti]/...\f[R] for a home\-relative path
.IP \[bu] 2
An absolute path inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
A relative path resolved from the current working directory, which must
end up inside \f[CR]$HOME\f[R]
.SH IGNORE SUPPORT
Tildr supports a repository\-level \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R] file for
excluding paths from repository scans.
.IP \[bu] 2
The file must live at the root of the Tildr repository
.IP \[bu] 2
Ignore rules are applied when scanning repository contents
.IP \[bu] 2
Patterns follow gitignore\-style matching semantics
.PP
Example:
.IP
.EX
*.log
cache/
\&.DS_Store
.EE
.SH INTERNALLY EXCLUDED PATHS
During repository scans, Tildr always excludes the following entries
regardless of \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R]:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR].git\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Root \f[CR].gitignore\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Root \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR].tildr/\f[R] \[em] internal directory containing all Tildr
configuration files
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR].DS_Store\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]Thumbs.db\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR].gitkeep\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Files ending in \f[CR].tmp\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Files ending in \f[CR].swp\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Files ending in \f[CR]\[ti]\f[R]
.PP
The root control files are context\-sensitive.
Files named \f[CR].gitignore\f[R] or \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R] under
\f[CR]common/\f[R] or \f[CR]profiles/<name>/\f[R] are managed HOME
dotfiles.
Files ending in \f[CR].bak\f[R] can also be managed; add
\f[CR]*.bak\f[R] to \f[CR].tildrignore\f[R] to exclude them explicitly.
.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
When set, disables all colored output regardless of
\f[CR]core.color\f[R] config.
.TP
\f[B]EDITOR\f[R]
Editor used by \f[CR]tildr edit\f[R].
Falls back to \f[CR]$VISUAL\f[R], then \f[CR]nano\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]VISUAL\f[R]
Alternative editor used by \f[CR]tildr edit\f[R] if \f[CR]$EDITOR\f[R]
is not set.
.TP
\f[B]PAGER\f[R]
Pager used by \f[CR]tildr cat \-\-less\f[R] and
\f[CR]tildr status \-\-less\f[R].
Falls back to \f[CR]less \-RFX\f[R].
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/tildr/config.toml\f[R]
User configuration file.
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.dotfiles/.tildr/\f[R]
Internal Tildr directory containing encrypted\-items, encrypted.gpg,
groups.json, and profiles.json.
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.dotfiles/.tildrignore\f[R]
User\-defined ignore patterns.
